### Footnotes

<span id="fn_1408"></span>[341:2](sbe31080.htm#fr_1420.md) This chapter 1-5
follows Y. XI, 1-8 in the Vendîdâd Sâdah; so, appropriately.

<span id="fn_1409"></span>[341:3](sbe31080.htm#fr_1421.md) The Ratu answers
for all according to the rubric printed by Westergaard, but of later
origin than the text. It arose from the fact that the several offices
were later united in that of the Ratu. Originally the corresponding
official answered to his title. The Hâvanan was the Mobad who pounded
the Haoma in the mortar.

<span id="fn_1410"></span>[341:4](sbe31080.htm#fr_1422.md) The Mobad who
fed the Fire.

<span id="fn_1411"></span>[341:5](sbe31080.htm#fr_1423.md) The Mobad who
aided the presentations.

<span id="fn_1412"></span>[341:6](sbe31080.htm#fr_1424.md) The water
carrier.

<span id="fn_1413"></span>[342:1](sbe31080.htm#fr_1425.md) The washer.

<span id="fn_1414"></span>[342:2](sbe31080.htm#fr_1426) The mixer (?.md),
or the Mobad who attended to disinfections.

<span id="fn_1415"></span>[342:3](sbe31080.htm#fr_1427.md) The Mobad who
attended to penance.

<span id="fn_1416"></span>[342:4](sbe31080.htm#fr_1428.md) The typical
layman.

<span id="fn_1417"></span>[342:5](sbe31080.htm#fr_1429.md) This important
custom was fully treated in the lost Nask, No. 16 (or No. 18, by another
reckoning).

<span id="fn_1418"></span>[342:6](sbe31080.htm#fr_1430.md) So the most, but
ratukhshathra means elsewhere 'ruling in the ritual as supreme.'

<span id="fn_1419"></span>[343:1](sbe31080.htm#fr_1431.md) This section
follows Y. XI, 9-15 in the V.S., preceding a section described as Y. XI,
59, 60, in the B.V.S.

<span id="fn_1420"></span>[343:2](sbe31080.htm#fr_1433.md) Probably in an
imperative sense, or, with some, an infinitive.

<span id="fn_1421"></span>[343:3](sbe31080.htm#fr_1434.md) Read Zaotasti
which contains sandhi. It seems a gloss to explain the Âthraom (sic). It
is zaotâ asti.

